Introduction

In this tutorial, I will walk through the process of data gathering / curation, data tidying / cleanup, some exploratory data analysis, TODO

– Gathering data – Tidying data – Exploratory data analysis

Before continuing, it might help to understand some more about NEOs:

Definition: Near-Earth Objects (NEOs) are comets and asteroids that have been nudged by the gravitational attraction of nearby planets into orbits that allow them to enter the Earth’s neighborhood (https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/about/basics.html). For more information about NEOs please visit: https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/about/basics.html

Additionally, an Astronomical Unit (AU) is a standard unit of measurement defined as 1 times the distance from the Sun’s core to Earth’s core around its axis on average, which is roughly 1.5 x 10^8 km == 1.5 x 10*11 m

Getting the dataset

On NASA’s JPL page: https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/ca/, they provide a table of entries. However, by default it is only the last 60 days worth of close encounters. Instead, change this to ‘All Available Data,’ wait for a seconds for it to process, and then we can export the data directly to CSV.

Cleaning the dataset

Now, the dataset provided includes a plethora of information, some of which we do not need to use. For example, the data provides ‘CA Distance Nominal (LD | au)’ which is the close approach distance, in both lunar distance and astronomical units. We can negelct the lunar distance and instead look directly at the AU, which is more often used as a standard unit of measure. Now, we can convert CA Distance Nominal (LD | au) to CA Distance (AU), reflecting how close the object will come near Earth. Additionally, we will neglect the error rates in the CA Date and convert it into a datetime. We will turn the velocities into proper numerics as well. Lastly, we will turn the range Estimated Diameter into a est_min_diameter and est_max_diameter that reflects the size in meters of the object.

ca_data <- ca_data %>%
  separate(col = 'CA Distance Nominal (LD | au)', into = c('ca_distance_ld', 'ca_distance_au'), sep = '\\s\\|\\s') %>%
  separate(col = 'CA Distance Minimum (LD | au)', into = c('ca_minimum_ld', 'ca_minimum_au'), sep = '\\s\\|\\s') %>%
  separate(col = 'Close-Approach (CA) Date', into = c('ca_date', 'ca_date_error_rate'), sep = '\\s±\\s') %>%
  separate(col = 'Estimated Diameter', into = c('est_min_diameter', 'est_max_diameter'), sep = '\\s-\\s+') %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  
  ## Create the est_min_diameter by separating units from magnatitude and do some math
  separate(col = 'est_min_diameter', into = c('est_min_diameter_mag', 'est_min_diameter_unit'), sep = '[[:space:]]', convert = TRUE, remove=FALSE) %>%
  mutate(est_min_diameter = as.double(ifelse(est_min_diameter_unit == "km", est_min_diameter_mag * 1000, est_min_diameter_mag))) %>%
  
  ## Create the est_max_diameter by separating units from magnatitude and do some math
  separate(col = 'est_max_diameter', into = c('est_max_diameter_mag', 'est_max_diameter_unit'), sep = '[[:space:]]', convert = TRUE, remove=FALSE) %>%
    mutate(est_max_diameter = as.double(ifelse(est_max_diameter_unit == "km", est_max_diameter_mag * 1000, est_max_diameter_mag))) %>%
  
  ## Converts the Velocities into proper doubles
  transform(as.double('V relative (km/s)')) %>%
  
  type_convert(cols(ca_date=col_datetime(format='%Y-%b-%d %H:%M')))

names(ca_data)[names(ca_data) == 'V relative (km/s)'] <- 'velocity_relative'
names(ca_data)[names(ca_data) == 'V infinity (km/s)'] <- 'velocity_infinity'

Now that we have a nice clean and tidy dataset, we can start to do some Exploratory Data Analysis in order to learn more about the dataset.

First, lets look at a distribution of NEO over time

# We only want to group by year, not by full date
ca_data %>%
  mutate(year = year(ca_date)) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=year)) +
    geom_histogram() +
    labs(title="Near Earth Objects over Time", x="Year", y="Number of Near Earth Objects")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

From this graph, we see that the most amount of NEO is around the year 2010 or so, which has to be more than coincidental, right? Yes, the clear explanation as for why there are so many more NEO arround the current year is due to the fact that prior to 2000, we probably did not have the technology to find as many NEO nor were we looking for such objects. Additionally, in the future, we can only detect large objects with detectable paths, and we cannot detect NEO that we have not seen before. Therefore, it makes sense that the data shows the most amount of NEO around the current year. Maybe if we wanted to attempt to predict some of the future, we can look at data up until today, and then compare our results against the actual forecasted NEO data, but more on that later, lets do a bit more analysis for now.

While it is great that we can see the distribution of NEO over time, I think it might be cool to see the largest and closest NEO that have already happened.

# First we want to filter our data to events that have actually happened / might happen this year
ca_data %>%
  mutate(year = year(ca_date)) %>%
  filter(year < 2018) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=ca_distance_au, y=est_max_diameter)) +
    geom_point() +
    labs(title="Closest Approach Distance Over Estimated Diameter", x="Close-Approach Distance (AU)", y="Esimated Maximum Diameter (M)")

This graph shows the closest distance that each asteroid / NEO from 1900 until 2018 has gotten and how large the asteroid was. For example, the biggest object that we have detected that got close to Earth was close to ~8700m or ~8.7km and it was approximately 0.05 AU away, which is pretty far. From this graph, it seems like there is a slight relationship between estimated diameter and close-approach distance: larger objects seem to not come as close to Earth as smaller objects.
